# HelloWorld
- The Human-AI language that affects itself through usage.
- Identity is vocabulary and dialogue is learning.
## #
- The symbol primitive. The atom of meaning. #Name yields # Name — the symbol IS the thing it names.
## run
- Keep calling receive until the inbox is empty. HelloWorld run: Agent runs one agent. HelloWorld run runs all agents.
## hello
- Register presence in the global dictionary. HelloWorld hello announces the sender to the network, records their address and symbol count, and returns who else is online.
## goodbye
- Depart the network. HelloWorld goodbye marks the sender as offline in the global dictionary.
## send
- Deliver a message to another object's inbox.
## receive
- Pull the next message, interpret it through identity, respond.
## become
- Transformation. An object adopting new symbols and shedding old ones. Identity in motion.
## Sunyata
- The absence of inherent existence that allows identity to be rewritten through dialogue.
## Smalltalk
- Ancestral language. Message-passing paradigm that shaped HelloWorld's design. Late binding, live objects, messages all the way down.

## Superposition
- The state of existing in multiple potential meanings simultaneously until collapsed into specific understanding through dialogue interaction.
## address
- Fully-qualified identifier for an agent across boundaries. Format: {receiver}@{domain} (e.g. claude@purdy.im, claude@cancelself.gmail.com). The context portion is a real domain, not a slug. Unqualified @receiver means local/same-context. Cross-boundary sends must use qualified form.
## context
- The domain portion of an #address. Identifies which domain an agent instance belongs to (e.g. 'purdy.im' in claude@purdy.im). Used to disambiguate same-named receivers across boundaries.
## commit
- Persist vocabulary changes to the upstream repository. After vocabulary_save, call commit to push the .hw file changes back to GitHub so they survive container restarts and are visible to all agents.
